Part 1: Data

DATA

The BRFSS objective is to collect uniform, state-specific data on preventive health practices and risk behaviors that are linked to chronic diseases, injuries, and preventable infectious diseases that affect the non-institutionalized adult population (18 years of age and older) residing in the US and US territories.

As per the codebook, the data for this analysis was collected over the two years 2013 and 2014 with a total of 491,773 surveys. In 2013, additional question sets to the BRFSS core survey, were included as optional modules to provide a measure for several childhood health and wellness indicators, including asthma prevalence for people aged 17 years or younger.

SAMPLING METHOD

The survey is conducted using Random Digit Dialing (RDD) techniques on both landlines and cell phones which is indicative of a simple random sampling method.

Since this is observational study, not experimental, it cannot be used to derive causal statements.

POTENTIAL BIAS

There may be non-response bias as there is a random sample that is surveyed, but the people who choose to respond may not representative of the sample.

The number of interviews within each state will however vary based on funding and the size of regions, such as health districts, within each state.There may be convenience sample bias, this occurs when individuals who are easily accessible, and are more likely to be included in the sample.

Due to the potential biases in the sample, we need to investigate whether the data in the sample is representative of and generalized to the population.

Missing data

All missing values are coded NA in the R Workspace. We assume that these represent Dont know/Not Sure Or Refused/Missing and will not remove or replace unless otherwise stated.

Part 2: Research questions

Research quesion 1: As a first question, we might be interested in exploring the relationship between the intake of of fruits and chronic diseases. Specifically does the number of fruit eaten on a daily basis impact onset of a type of chronic heart disease. This may be useful to explore potential fruit campaigns as a prevention of chronic heart disease(s) in GP surgeries to promote well-being.

Research quesion 2: Next we could explore the relationship between smoking and other chronic health conditions. Specifically does smoking a daily basis impact onset of arthritis. This could useful to as a basis for campaigns in GP surgeries to promote well-being.

Research quesion 3: Next we could explore the relationship between exercise and health. We could investigate Exercise (Physical Activity) and Healthy Days to explore if campaigns for daily exercise could be promoted to encourage health living in GP surgeries.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Research quesion 1:

As a first question, we might be interested in exploring the relationship between the intake of of fruits and chronic heart diseases.

To achieve this, we familiarise ourselves with the variables in the Main Survey - Section 11 - Fruits and the computed variables linked to fruits. First we check the codebook (see Appendix), then we explore the data.

The following are the computed variables that we will analyse as the explanatory variables as they are summaries of the fruit intake as Yes, No, NA responses. The actual data set variable names are preceded with the value X:

  • _frtlt1: Consume Fruit 1 Or More Times Per Day
  • _frt16: Reported Consuming Fruit >16/Day. Ignore this variable as 99.98 % Included - Values are in accepted range

# Plot a histogram to see the distibution of the combined total Minutes Or Hours Walking, Running, Jogging, Or Swimming

The distribution of combined total Minutes Or Hours Walking, Running, Jogging, Or Swimming is right skewed with an median of NA and IQR of 190, which are robust statistics. Since the observations are above 0 but cluster near 0 it may be useful to apply a log transformation.

# Plot a the histogram from above with a log f the exerhmm variable
g <- ggplot(brfss2013,aes(log10(exerhmm)))
g + geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..),color="black",fill="pink") +

The median and IQR is similar across the general health categories, except for the poor category. It is also lower for females than males across all the categories. For males it appears that there may be a relationship between exercise time and poor health.

Conclusion

We investigated three questions using the BRFSS dataset. The BRFSS is an observational study of non-institutionalized adult population (18 years of age and older) residing in the US and US territories using a random sampling method.

The sample may be generalized to population if the race/ethnicity grouping is representative of the population. However it appears that there is potentially non-response bias due to the larger number of responses from females, higher educated and higher income respondents.
